  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#add8ff" WIDTH="150"><B>Analysis</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">&quot;We are of [the] opinion the district<BR ALIGN='left'/>court&#x27;s finding that Franklin Russell,<BR ALIGN='left'/>Senior, was not in `control&#x27; of taxpayer<BR ALIGN='left'/>corporation `immediately after the<BR ALIGN='left'/>transfer&#x27; on July 16, 1924 and<BR ALIGN='left'/>therefore, that Section 112(b)(5) did<BR ALIGN='left'/>not apply, is abundantly supported by<BR ALIGN='left'/>the evidence.&quot; Id. at 959.\nThe<BR ALIGN='left'/>evidence, of course, was that unlike<BR ALIGN='left'/>Stanton, Franklin Russell, Sr. had<BR ALIGN='left'/>undertaken by a contract supported by<BR ALIGN='left'/>consideration, prior to the transfer, to<BR ALIGN='left'/>give his son one-half the business. Thus<BR ALIGN='left'/>he did not at the time of the transfer<BR ALIGN='left'/>have the absolute right to designate who<BR ALIGN='left'/>would receive all the stock in the<BR ALIGN='left'/>transferee. That distinction suffices,<BR ALIGN='left'/>and we need not consider whether, as the<BR ALIGN='left'/>government contends, Fahs was<BR ALIGN='left'/>erroneously decided since Franklin<BR ALIGN='left'/>Russell, Jr. was in practical effect, a<BR ALIGN='left'/>50% owner of the transferred enterprise.<BR ALIGN='left'/>That would, of course, have caused the<BR ALIGN='left'/>aggregation of his and his father&#x27;s<BR ALIGN='left'/>control, and have made the<BR ALIGN='left'/>reorganization tax-free. Even if the<BR ALIGN='left'/>record supported a finding that prior to<BR ALIGN='left'/>November 1, 1966 Mrs. Stanton had<BR ALIGN='left'/>acquired in some binding manner a 49%<BR ALIGN='left'/>interest in the transferred enterprise<BR ALIGN='left'/>(and nothing in the record so suggests)</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
